    'Information and Ideas Central Ideas and Details Difficulty Question ID 124fdcd7 ID: 124fdcd7 Many archaeologists will tell you that categorizing excavated fragments of pottery by style, period, and what objects they belong to relies not only on standard criteria, but also on instinct developed over years of practice. In a recent study, however, researchers trained a deep-learning computer model on thousands of images of pottery fragments and found that it could categorize them as accurately as a team of expert archaeologists. Some archaeologists have expressed concern that they might be replaced by such computer models, but the researchers claim that outcome is highly unlikely. Which finding, if true, would most directly support the researchers’ claim? archaeologists could. fragments that were presented. other important tasks that only human experts can do. fragments.',
